:: prologue_greg_office
<!-- EPISODE 1: The Deal -->

The fluorescent lights hum their hymn of mediocrity. Greg, VP of Engineering, leans back in his chair like a man who has never written a line of code but has read exactly one article about "AI leverage."

"Bring him in Monday," Greg says. His smile doesn't reach his eyes. It doesn't reach anywhere.

You don't know a guy. You know a guy who knows a guy who once used ChatGPT to write a wedding toast. That's it. That's the whole network.

But you said yes anyway.

[[["Head home."|prologue_walk_home]]]

:: prologue_walk_home
The evening air is thick with the smell of money burning. Not yours — not yet — but the premonition of it. Your apartment building rises like a courthouse at the end of a long hallway.

You open the door.

Sarah is on the couch. Leg elevated. The silence in the room has a different texture than it used to. The kids are fighting over a broken iPad screen. The mortgage statement sits on the counter like a small, polite suicide note.

She looks up. "The car was fine," she says. "The other guy wasn't."

Three months. No work. A three-car pileup that somehow involved no cars. The insurance is a fog. The savings account is a rumor.

> **A) Clear the table. Grind Linear Algebra from first principles before Monday or die of a caffeine-induced heart murmur.**

[["Grind."|path_a_grind]]

> **B) Sell your IBM Model M and 1998 'Vim Power User' shirt on eBay.**

[["Liquidate."|path_b_liquidate]]

> **C) Create "The Guy" — a deep-fake LinkedIn and a CV written in the language of the Snake. 🐍**

[["Fabricate."|path_c_create_guy]]

:: path_a_grind
You clear the kitchen table. Coffee. Whiteboard markers. A dog-eared copy of _Pattern Recognition and Machine Learning_ that you've been pretending to read since 2019.

The hours blur. Eigenvectors. Backpropagation. You drink so much coffee your hands start to look like they'd shake during a drug test.

By 4am you're staring at a whiteboard covered in notation that could qualify as abstract art.

Monday arrives like a freight train with no brakes.

[["Go to the meeting."|episode_2_monday]]

:: path_b_liquidate
You open eBay. The IBM Model M fetches $140 from a collector in Berlin. The shirt — size Large, never washed, mint condition irony — goes for $43 to a Portland startup founder who wasn't alive in 1998.

It is not enough.

But it buys two weeks of breathing room.

[["Continue."|episode_2_monday]]

:: path_c_create_guy
You sit in the dark for exactly eleven minutes. Then you open a browser.

First: LinkedIn. You create a profile. "Kieran Voss — AI Solutions Architect. Ex-DeepMind. Current: Independent LLM Consultant (Fortune 500 Focus)." Headshot: generated. Employee count at his fictional "Kairos AI Advisory" firm: three. All of them Kieran.

Then the CV. You write it in the language of snakes. "Orchestrated multi-agent LLM pipelines at scale." "Reduced token overhead by 47% through deterministic sampling strategies." It sounds like it means something. It might mean nothing. Greg won't know the difference.

You hit save.

[["Continue."|episode_2_monday]]

:: episode_2_monday
<!-- EPISODE 2 PENDING — this is where your thread continues. -->

[This is where your next post picks up. The Monday meeting. Greg. The Guy.]

